ment in federal detention, followed by their appearance in deportation proceedings and release from custody, and, finally, ending with their struggle to build new lives in the United States. This book shows how the U.S. government got into the business of detaining children and what we can learn from this troubled history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCentral AmericanszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal alien childrenxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal immigrationxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aImmigration enforcementzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aJuvenile detentionzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aMexicanszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aNoncitizen childrenxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUnaccompanied immigrant childrenxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096144940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961449/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles